course: main course
servings: 2
---

Fill a #pot{} with @water{700%ml} and add the @saffron{1} and @vegetable stock pot{1}. Bring to the boil on high heat.

While your stock heats up, prepare your veggies. Cut the leafy top from the @fennel{1} and keep to one side. Cut your fennel bulb in half lengthways. Remove the tough core at the base (see picture) and then cut into slices about the width of your little finger. Cut the @echalion shallot{1} in half through the root, peel and then chop into 1/2cm chunks (or as small as you can!).

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one) and cut the top and bottom off the @courgette{1}. Cut your courgette at an angle into 1cm thick slices. Roughly chop your fennel top. Keep to one side.

Heat a #frying pan{} over high heat and add a splash of @oil{}. When the oil is hot, add your fennel slices and cook for ~{5%minutes}, stirring frequently until nicely caramelised and soft enough to eat. Once cooked, remove from the pan and keep to one side. Wipe out the pan with some #kitchen paper{}, we will use it again later.

Now for your risotto! Place a #wide bottomed saucepan{} on medium heat and add half the @Netherend salted butter{30%g}. When your butter has melted, add your shallot. Cook for ~{3%minutes}, stirring frequently until your shallot is soft. Add your garlic, cook for another ~{1%minute} and then add the @risotto rice{175%g}. Stir well to make sure your rice is nicely coated in your butter.

Add a ladleful of your boiling stock to your rice and stir with long sweeping motions until your stock is almost absorbed. Add another ladleful of stock, stir again and repeat this process until nearly all of your stock is absorbed by your rice. This should take around ~{15-17%minutes}.

> Welcome to the art of making the perfect risotto! The risotto is cooked when the rice has the tiniest bite left in it and the consistency is that of porridge.

Return the frying pan you used for your fennel to high heat. Cook your courgette slices for ~{3%minutes} on each side. Don't be tempted to turn them too quickly, they need to char and blacken slightly. Pop your courgette slices on a #chopping board{} and allow to cool before cutting in half.

Finish your risotto by stirring in your fennel slices and fennel top, half the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and your remaining butter. Add a squeeze of @lemon{1} juice and taste your risotto to check the seasoning. Add @salt{} and @black pepper{} if necessary.

Serve your risotto in a #bowl{} and arrange some of your courgette on top. Finish with some @Steve's Leaves Peashoots{1%handful} and a final sprinkling of hard Italian cheese.

> Do not use alternative greens for the peashoots - the specific flavour and texture makes this dish special!